I used two different reduction techniques because there were high losses when using "sum" reduction.
I swapped between a "sum" and "mean" loss, where the loss of the mean was lower.

The contrastive loss did not help the umap in the sum reduction methods, but it did in the mean cases.
In the mean reduction case, there was poor seperation when observing the standard vae latent space, but patterns began to arise with the contrastive umap space. 

** Triplet Fingerprint Reconstruction
The introduction of triplet loss should not improve the reconstruction because it restricts the models freedom to choose the optimal spot for a fingerprint.
The fingerprint has to also satisfy the triplet margins.

** Dimensionality Sweep
I can look at the reconstruction loss, the KL divergence, and the clustering quality.

For the reconstruction loss, dimensionality increases means the loss will decrease until it plateaus.
The point where it plateaus is the elbow, which is the point between underfitting and overfitting.

For the KL divergence, when the decoder decides extra dimensions aren't useful, the divergence drops to 0.
Choosing the dimension right before this occurs is best.

A more heuristic approach is to look at the clustering quality where there will be well defined clusters.

** Evaluation of latent model
I would take an affine combination of latent vectors for two similar molecules.
The resulting vectors should represent a smooth trajectory in the latent space and the decoder should decode the points on this trajectory to similar molecules to the original two.
The more smooth the latent spaces trajectory is is a measure of how well it represents the data. 

